TaggingExampleComponentEXAMPLE1Title: Using location to group fleet data
TaggingExampleComponentEXAMPLE2Title: Creating access control based on data
TaggingExampleComponentEXAMPLE1Descripti: Fleets can use location tags to efficiently group your fleet data into region specific grouping and also use it for access control. For example, a trucking company can tag their truck based on states like
, or based on cities such as
etc. You can also assign tag to users so that
they can only view data from assets that belong under that tag.
TaggingExampleComponentEXAMPLE2Descripti: Fleets can use tagging to create access controls for users such as fleet managers, safety coaches to view data based on some sort of segmentation. For example, a fleet having tags such as
can assign safety coach then it will show data based on these tags.
TaggingExampleComponentEXAMPLE3Descripti: Tags can come in very handy when you have to create custom filter based on your fleet needs. For example, suppose a fleet wants to view unrecognized trips then they can assign
tag for each and every trip in which the driver was not recognized and then they can easily surface the list of unrecognized trips.
TaggingFAQComponentGeneralQ2: Who can create attributes & tags for the fleet?
TaggingFAQComponentGeneralQ3: How can tags benefit my fleet?
TaggingFAQComponentGeneralQ4: Can a fleet opt out of tagging if not required?
TaggingFAQComponentGeneralA1: With tagging, fleets can easily manage and group data by location, business type, assets and other types of data. You can use location tags to efficiently group your fleet data into region specific grouping and also use it for access control.
TaggingFAQComponentGeneralA2: Only administrators can create/edit/delete attribute and tags.
TaggingFAQComponentGeneralA3: Tags can help fleets to group data as per their needs, provide access control based on data etc.
TaggingFAQComponentGeneralA4: Yes, the whole tagging feature is optional for the fleet.
TaggingFAQComponentAttributesA1: Attributes are like logical group of tags you will be creating. For example, you can have Location as an attribute and under that you can create North, South, East and West as tags.
TaggingFAQComponentAttributesA2: No attributes are only visible to administrators and only use of attributes is to provide a logical grouping of tags.
TaggingFAQComponentAttributesA3: Yes, you can activate or deactivate an attribute any time you want and once deactivated the tags will not be visible on the portal.
TaggingFAQComponentTagsQ2: Is there any limit on the number of tags?
TaggingFAQComponentTagsQ3: What happens when I edit or delete a tag?
TaggingFAQComponentTagsA1: Tags are custom keywords you can create based on your fleet that will help you to assign these keywords to trips, assets, incidents etc. For example, you can assign North tag to any asset to specify its location.
TaggingFAQComponentTagsA2: Yes, you can create a maximum of upto 1024 tags under each attribute.
TaggingFAQComponentTagsA3: When you edit a tag, the changes will take time to reflect on the portal, whereas once you delete a tag, all entities attached to that tag will be removed.
TaggingFAQComponentEntitiesQ2: Can I add or edit existing entities?
TaggingFAQComponentEntitiesQ3: How does tagging work with entities?
TaggingFAQComponentEntitiesA1: Entities are fixed set of objects which can be physical or virtual in nature. For example, you can assign a location tag North to entities such as Drivers or Assets.
TaggingFAQComponentEntitiesA2: No, the entities are fixed set and mostly comprises of assets, drivers, trips or incidents.
TaggingFAQComponentEntitiesA3: In tag management page, you can attach attributes for each entity and then the tags which are part of that attributes will be shown when assigning  tags for that entity.
TaggingOnBoardingComponentDescription1: Introducing tagging, by which any size of fleets can easily manage and group data by location, business type, assets and other types of data.
TaggingOnBoardingComponentDescription2: You can use location tags to efficiently group your fleet data into region specific grouping and also use it for access control. For example, a trucking company can tag their truck based on states like New York or Ohio, or based on cities such as Chicago, Houston etc. You can also assign tag to users so that they can only view data from assets that belong under that tag.

homeAnnBannerImportantSubText1: Introducing User Roles, empowering you with tailored access and privileges to the portal, ensuring a personalized and secure experience like never before.
homeAnnBannerImportantSubText2: Please click on the 'View Details' button for more information.
annBannerSubText1: Please check the below FAQ's to know more about the User Role feature.
annBannerA1a: User roles is a feature that allows the Fleet Administrator to create custom roles based on a set of permissions and UI configurations.Once created, they can assign one of these custom roles to a given user. The user assigned to a specific role will inherit all the permissions and UI configurations that have been given to the defined role.
annBannerA1b: This feature allows one to manage user permissions in an organized or structured way. It is immensely helpful when one has to manage a large number of users in the system/portal.
annBannerQ2: How does it affect me as a portal user?
annBannerA2a: With the introduction of user roles in production deployment, the end user on the fleet portal may see some changes to the UI or in terms of the functionality that he/she has seen in the past. The user may no longer see some pages for which they no longer has permission to.
annBannerA2b: If the user does not see the page through which permissions to other users were given (applies to admin users in the fleet who had such access to earlier), he/she will have to contact the TSP customer support for more information.
annBannerQ3: Does it require any change from my side?
annBannerA3a: Yes, there are some actions required on your side if you are a user of the portal based on what role you belong to. Please check below what action is required from your end based on your role:
annBannerA3b: If you are a Fleet Administrator -
annBannerA3c: Please share the list of users who act as Fleet Administrators in your fleet to the TSP/service provider.
annBannerA3d: If you are a Fleet Manager or any other role -
annBannerA3e: You will be assigned the role of a Fleet Manager. This will give you all the permissions except for User Management. For more information, contact your Administrator.
annBannerQ4: What if I don't want to use User Roles?
annBannerA4a: From the next release onwards User roles feature will be the default way to manage users for all portals. The legacy way of managing permissions to each user in the portal will be deprecated. By default, we will follow the below rule to assign roles to users:
annBannerA4c: Any user who has access to user management
annBannerA4e: Any user who doesn't have access to user management
annBannerQ5: Whom to contact if I face any issues with the new feature?
annBannerA5a: Please contact your Administrator/Service Provider, if you are facing any issues with your login post-user role feature is released in production.
